My Return to Ghana: The Early 90s — When I Saw Home With New Eyes
*By Ulric Kelly*

My return to Ghana in the early 90s was truly amazing.

I had been away long enough for home to become a memory — the sound of highlife from a distant radio, the taste of kelewele wrapped in newspaper, the smell of the earth after the first rains. When I finally landed at Kotoka, it all came rushing back at once.

What struck me first was not just the familiarity, but the possibility. Everywhere I looked, I, Ulric Kelly, could see vast opportunities that were just waiting to be touched. Economically, commercially, culturally — the country was wide open. The markets in Accra and Takoradi were buzzing with traders, farmers bringing in plantain, cassava, and palm fruits, fishermen pulling their nets at Busua and Butre at dawn. Small shops were becoming businesses. Businesses were dreaming of becoming industries. You could feel that Ghana was on the verge of something big.

And then there was the culture. Oh, the culture!

To see it all over again with adult eyes was a gift. The durbars, the drums, the language — the deep, proud Ahanta I heard in the streets of Agona Nkwanta. The respect for elders, the way a stranger becomes family after one shared bowl of fufu. The funerals that celebrate life, the festivals that tell history without a single textbook. I had forgotten how rich we are. Not rich in cedi or dollar, but rich in identity.

I really enjoyed my stay. Every morning was a discovery. Every conversation was a lesson. I traveled, I listened, I reconnected with family and land. I sat under mango trees and just listened to stories. In the quiet moments, I realized how much I had been missing.

When I boarded my flight back to the States, I was not the same man who had arrived weeks earlier. I came back with a sense of fulfillment and well-being that I had not felt in years. My shoulders were lighter. My mind was clearer.

Henceforth, I had a better outlook. I saw Ghana not as a place I left, but as a place that never left me. And I saw America not as an escape, but as a tool — a place to gather knowledge, resources, and experience to one day bring back home.

That trip in the early 90s did not just give me memories. It gave me a mission.

That mission still drives me today.

Ulric Kelly


